logy, psychical research, and the psychology of religion. Moreover, Taylor's work shows that out of his scientific study of consciousness, James formulated a sophisticated metaphysics of radical empiricism. In light of historical developments in psychology, as well as the current philosophic implications of the neuroscience revolution related to the biology of consciousness, Taylor argues that both the subject matter of James's investigations and his metaphysics of radical empiricism are just as important for psychology today as James believed they were in his own time.This book represents a major new contribution both to James scholarship and to the history of American psychology. Although philosophers have analyzed radical empiricism, this book is the first to trace the development of radical empiricism as a metaphysics addressed to psychologists. It is also the first to show James's involvement in depth-psychology and psychotherapeutics and to trace historical continuity between James's work on consciousness and subsequent developments in psychoanalysis, personality theory, and humanistic psychology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / History.2bisacsh  aAwakened Consciousness.  aBuddhism.  aCambridge Metaphysical Club.  aChild Study movement.  aChristian Scientists.  aCritique philosophique.  aDemon possession.  aErkenntnisstheorie.  aGerman idealism.  aHansen and Lehmann.  aJames-Lange theory.  aJamesean psychology.  aKant.  aLibrary of Congress.  aabnormal psychology.  aalternating personality.  aassociationism.  aautomatic writing.  acensus on hallucinations.  acerebral localization.  acharacter development.  acognitive psychology.  adissociated states.  adynamic psychotherapy.  aevolutionary functionalism.  aexistentialism.  aexperimental measuremen